
<h1>ML Security</h1>

<div class="chapter-meta">
  <span class="tag">Chapter 18: Responsible AI and Ethics</span>
  <span class="tag">Section 4</span>
</div>

<p>I avoided ML security for an embarrassingly long time. Every time a paper about adversarial examples came across my feed, I'd skim the abstract, think "neat trick, won't affect me," and move on. I built models, deployed them behind APIs, scraped training data from the internet, and downloaded pre-trained weights from model hubs—all without once asking what could go wrong <em>at the model level</em>. Then a colleague showed me a spam classifier that was 99.3% accurate on every benchmark and also contained a hidden backdoor that let specific emails sail right through. The model passed every test we had. The backdoor was invisible to us. That was the wake-up call. Here is that dive.</p>

<p>ML security is the study of how machine learning systems can be attacked and defended—not at the network or infrastructure layer, but at the level of data, gradients, model weights, and prompts. The field emerged around 2014 with Goodfellow's discovery of adversarial examples and has since expanded to cover everything from training-time poisoning to model theft to prompt injection in large language models.</p>

<p>Before we start, a heads-up. We're going to be working through gradient computations, optimization objectives, and a bit of information theory, but you don't need any of that in advance. We'll add the concepts we need one at a time, with explanation.</p>

<p>This isn't a short journey, but I hope you'll be glad you came.</p>

